I did search for other reported issues, but I wasn't too sure about whether or not the problem or the source of it was discussed already.
But in any case I suspect it might have to do something with #28627.

### Include provider and version information

EF Core version: 8.0.2
Database provider: Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.Sqlite, Npgsql.EntityFrameworkCore.PostgreSQL (Both 8.0.2)
Target framework: .NET 8
Operating system: Windows 11
IDE: Jetbrains Rider 2023.3.3

Edit: removed issue number

## Issue description
When using `ExecuteUpdateAsync` to update a complex property's value, the operation fails if the `DbSet` has been filtered with a `.Where` predicate that requires a (slightly complicated?) JOIN to be performed.  
The relevant part of the error is `The following lambda argument to 'SetProperty' does not represent a valid property to be set`.  
(Sample code and relevant stack trace provided below this description chapter.)

I believe this must be an Npgsql-specific issue, because I also tried this with MS SQL server, and the update succeeded without errors there.

If at least one of the following is true, the error doesn't occur:
- The `.Where` filter is simpler, for example `.Where(v => v.Id == 1)` or `.Where(v => v.Comments.Any())`
- The property being updated isn't part of a complex property.

## Minimal reproduction
### Program.cs
```C#
using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;

var optionsBuilder = new DbContextOptionsBuilder<AppDbContext>();
optionsBuilder.UseNpgsql("User ID=postgres;Password=postgres;Host=localhost;Port=5432;Database=experiments;Include Error Detail=true");
await using var dbContext = new AppDbContext(optionsBuilder.Options);
await dbContext.Database.EnsureDeletedAsync();
await dbContext.Database.EnsureCreatedAsync();

var video = new Video
{
    Title = new TextTranslationKey
    {
        TextTranslations =
        [
            new TextTranslation
            {
                Locale = "en-US",
                Content = "Example title",
            },
        ],
    },
};
dbContext.Videos.Add(video);
await dbContext.SaveChangesAsync();

await dbContext.Videos
    // Removing this WHERE or using a different, simpler WHERE (e.g. .Where(v => v.Id == 1)) works fine
    .Where(v => v.Title!.TextTranslations!.Any())
    .ExecuteUpdateAsync(x => x.SetProperty(v => v.Settings.IsMonitored, false));

public class Video
{
    public int Id { get; init; }
    public TextTranslationKey? Title { get; init; }
    public VideoSettings Settings { get; init; } = new();
}

public class VideoSettings
{
    public bool IsMonitored { get; set; } = true;
}

public class TextTranslationKey
{
    public int Id { get; init; }
    public ICollection<TextTranslation>? TextTranslations { get; init; }
}

public class TextTranslation
{
    public int Id { get; init; }
    public int TextTranslationKeyId { get; init; }
    public TextTranslationKey? TextTranslationKey { get; init; }
    public required string Locale { get; init; }
    public required string Content { get; init; }
}

public class AppDbContext : DbContext
{
    public AppDbContext(DbContextOptions options) : base(options)
    {
    }

    public DbSet<Video> Videos => Set<Video>();
    public DbSet<TextTranslationKey> TextTranslationKeys => Set<TextTranslationKey>();
    public DbSet<TextTranslation> TextTranslations => Set<TextTranslation>();

    protected override void OnModelCreating(ModelBuilder modelBuilder)
    {
        base.OnModelCreating(modelBuilder);
        // Not using a complex property, i.e. with IsMonitored being just a simple property on Video, also works fine
        modelBuilder.Entity<Video>().ComplexProperty(p => p.Settings);
    }
}
```

